Quote: Rock, log, nettle-clump, bush, or tree-stump may, as chance determines, become the foster-parent of the 'placer'...
Notes:

Date: 27/1/1934
Source: Press, The  (Acland Glossary)
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: Placer - when a ewe dies, her lamb usually stays by her body .. he sometimes transfers his filial affection to some object close to where his mother died, perhaps a bush or large stone.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Kingdom in the Hills
Author: MCLEOD
Vol / Page: 110
Edition:
Quote: Lambs which lose their mothers when they are young sometimes form an attachment for an inanimate object like a bush or rock and become what are known as 'hermits', sometimes known as 'placer sheep.'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1989
Source: Dinkum Kiwi Dictionary, The
Author: MCGILL
Vol / Page: 81
Edition:
Quote: placer: a lamb whose mother has died and who has adopted a stone, bush or other object as a mother substitute. Australians also use the word for a lamb or sheep that stays in one place.
